Conditions make decisions:

if (sensorValue < 500) {
  // line detected — turn left
  leftMotor(50);
  rightMotor(150);
} else {
  // no line — go straight
  leftMotor(150);
  rightMotor(150);
}

This is the core of most robot programs.

The loop() function in Arduino runs forever:

void loop() {
  int sensorValue = analogRead(A0);
  if (sensorValue < 500) { turn(); }
  else { goStraight(); }
}

You don't write the loop yourself — Arduino calls this function repeatedly, hundreds of times per second.

Functions group code into reusable blocks:

void goForward() {
  digitalWrite(IN1, HIGH);
  digitalWrite(IN2, LOW);
  analogWrite(ENA, 150);
}

Now instead of writing 3 lines every time you want to go forward, you just call goForward().

